WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.060 --> 00:00:03.840
So welcome to this session, which is entitled The

2
00:00:03.880 --> 00:00:07.540
Dharma Master Yantai Advances in Targeted Therapy, and it

3
00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:09.400
focuses on immunotherapy and DNA repair.

4
00:00:11.020 --> 00:00:14.460
I'd like to read a statement on behalf of

5
00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:15.140
AACR.

6
00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:20.480
So Dharma Master Yantai, for whom this session is named, was a

7
00:00:20.500 --> 00:00:24.440
brave young abbess who dedicated her life to Dharma teaching.

8
00:00:24.740 --> 00:00:27.920
She was a never smoker who was diagnosed with lung cancer.

9
00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.680
Although not available to her at the time, targeted treatments are now

10
00:00:32.741 --> 00:00:36.400
available for the mutation that was identified in

11
00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:38.080
Dharma Yantai's cancer.

12
00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:42.420
According to her wishes and in memory of her, family

13
00:00:42.860 --> 00:00:46.680
established an endowment to support the Dharma Master Yantai Advances in

14
00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:47.860
Lung Cancer session.

15
00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:53.780
This family's goal is to foster cancer research that leads to

16
00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:57.460
new drugs development so that patients with cancer will live longer,

17
00:00:57.800 --> 00:01:01.760
have better quality of life, and potentially reach a cure in

18
00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:05.590
selected cases. So this was the citation that this

19
00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:06.740
session is dedicated to.

20
00:01:09.080 --> 00:01:11.830
With that, I'd like to kick off this

21
00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:15.100
session. There will be three speakers, including myself,

22
00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:20.100
and we will be focusing on the concept that

23
00:01:20.860 --> 00:01:24.740
when a diagnosis is made, we typically react

24
00:01:25.580 --> 00:01:28.360
based on the diagnosis. The idea that

25
00:01:28.420 --> 00:01:32.400
instead one can possibly change the diagnosis

26
00:01:32.460 --> 00:01:34.840
in favor of a better therapeutic outcome

27
00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.640
is pretty novel, and we will hear from the speakers

28
00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:43.300
several ways in which this potentially is possible or will

29
00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:44.090
become possible,

30
00:01:44.920 --> 00:01:48.440
including triggering cells to generate more

31
00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:49.160
neoantigens.

32
00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:54.180
And with that, it is my great pleasure to introduce the first speaker, that is

33
00:01:54.220 --> 00:01:55.250
Yardena Samuels.

34
00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:08.660
Hello, everybody, and welcome to the session.

35
00:02:09.241 --> 00:02:12.790
So indeed, I'll be talking about revisiting the

36
00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:15.860
neoantigen approach to cancer immunotherapy.

37
00:02:16.620 --> 00:02:19.020
I have no financial relationships to disclose.

38
00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:23.700
So it's well known that intratumor heterogeneity will determine

39
00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:27.820
how aggressive the tumor will be and how well it will

40
00:02:27.880 --> 00:02:31.840
respond to immunotherapy. And in fact, rather than thinking

41
00:02:31.860 --> 00:02:35.320
of intratumor heterogeneity as an additional hallmark of cancer,

42
00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:39.240
we actually think that it may be

43
00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:42.500
overlaid onto all the hallmarks of cancer.

44
00:02:42.549 --> 00:02:44.580
And this is a review that just came out

45
00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:49.220
in the special cell issue celebrating 25 years since the

46
00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:50.220
hallmarks of cancer,

47
00:02:51.040 --> 00:02:53.360
which was just published. And actually, Alberto

48
00:02:54.180 --> 00:02:58.160
co-published this with us as well, and so you're welcome to read more about our

49
00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:02.070
thoughts about this. But then when you start defining what

50
00:03:02.120 --> 00:03:04.970
intratumor heterogeneity actually is,

51
00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:09.480
you can determine it on many different levels: on the genetic

52
00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:13.240
level, the transcriptomic, epigenomic level, the proteomic

53
00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:16.580
level. All these three, the genetic,

54
00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:20.220
transcriptomic, and proteomic levels, will impact the

55
00:03:20.420 --> 00:03:23.520
immunopeptidome level, which is basically the landscape of

56
00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:27.320
neopeptides that are being presented on the tumor.

57
00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:31.180
And this immunopeptidome repertoire will shape how the immune system

58
00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:35.140
responds to the tumor. So you can think of the immunopeptidome as

59
00:03:35.180 --> 00:03:39.100
an additional definition of intratumor heterogeneity.

60
00:03:39.700 --> 00:03:43.360
Of course, intratumor heterogeneity is seen on the secretome, the drug

61
00:03:43.440 --> 00:03:46.540
sensitivity level, as well as the tumor

62
00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:50.220
microenvironment, which ultimately impacts the tumor

63
00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:53.980
state. But today I'll be exploring the immunopeptidome,

64
00:03:54.320 --> 00:03:58.120
and its level of heterogeneity. So we can think

65
00:03:58.220 --> 00:04:01.140
of the immunopeptidome heterogeneity on two levels.

66
00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:03.840
One is on the single cell level,

67
00:04:05.260 --> 00:04:08.900
but also across different cells within the tumor.

68
00:04:10.060 --> 00:04:14.000
Of course, we don't have single-cell immunopeptidomics at this point, and so

69
00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:16.780
the first level is pretty hard to determine.

70
00:04:16.800 --> 00:04:20.340
But identifying these neopeptides is of course extremely

71
00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:24.300
important because we have several different modalities that you

72
00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:28.280
can then use in order to treat

73
00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:31.980
the tumors, whether it's mRNA vaccines, TCR cognate,

74
00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:34.520
TCR T therapy, et cetera.

75
00:04:35.420 --> 00:04:38.900
Now, despite these neopeptides being extremely useful, there are several

76
00:04:38.920 --> 00:04:41.040
challenges in effectively targeting them.

77
00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:46.040
And so I will discuss some of these and ways that we think

78
00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:48.920
that we can solve these challenges.

79
00:04:48.980 --> 00:04:52.820
So first is that most neoantigens derive from passenger mutations, and so

80
00:04:52.840 --> 00:04:54.860
they're not recurrent across patients.

81
00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:58.400
The second is that few of them are effectively presented on MHC

82
00:04:58.480 --> 00:05:02.380
molecules. Third, neoantigens are often subclonal,

83
00:05:02.900 --> 00:05:05.080
and so they're easy targets for immunoevasion.

84
00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:09.070
And finally, especially in low TMB tumors, you will

85
00:05:09.180 --> 00:05:12.960
not have sufficient neoantigens, and that is

86
00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:17.740
most the focus of my talk. So regarding challenge number one,

87
00:05:18.400 --> 00:05:21.890
what our solution to the fact that most neoantigens are

88
00:05:21.980 --> 00:05:25.740
passenger-derived is that we have a data-driven approach to identify

89
00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:29.740
recurrently presented neoantigens, which basically means that we look at

90
00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:33.490
databases, identify recurrent somatic mutations,

91
00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:37.640
and then look at what HLA allotypes these exact same patients

92
00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:41.580
harbor, and only then we predict which neoantigens are going to be

93
00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:45.660
presented specifically for the HLA allotypes that are harbored

94
00:05:45.700 --> 00:05:49.640
by the patients who have this somatic mutation.

95
00:05:49.650 --> 00:05:53.130
And then we rank these lists, and we only focus on the ones that have

96
00:05:53.700 --> 00:05:57.040
potentially a high affinity of binding and are frequent within the

97
00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:57.880
population.

98
00:05:58.700 --> 00:06:02.520
We've done this quite a bit. At this point, we have a very large number of

99
00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:05.120
recurrent neopeptides that we've identified.

100
00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:07.890
We've proven them to be immunogenic.

101
00:06:07.960 --> 00:06:11.740
For most of them, we have cognate T cell receptors, and so these are relevant

102
00:06:11.760 --> 00:06:14.469
for about 350,000 patients

103
00:06:14.820 --> 00:06:18.696
yearly.Challenge number two is that few neoantigens are

104
00:06:18.736 --> 00:06:22.136
effectively presented by and targeted by the

105
00:06:22.196 --> 00:06:25.736
TCRs. So we have a few platforms in the lab in order to

106
00:06:25.816 --> 00:06:27.486
increase their presentation,

107
00:06:28.496 --> 00:06:32.326
and one of them, actually, I'm showing you here that was effective, which is that

108
00:06:32.356 --> 00:06:35.316
chemotherapy can enhance neoantigen-specific

109
00:06:35.356 --> 00:06:39.016
TCR-mediated killing. What we did here is we focused on

110
00:06:39.056 --> 00:06:42.856
KRAS G12V neoantigen, which we identified to be

111
00:06:43.136 --> 00:06:46.336
presented, and we also have our own cognate TCRs.

112
00:06:46.896 --> 00:06:49.816
And when we combine it with lymphodepleting

113
00:06:49.896 --> 00:06:53.736
chemotherapy, which is usually given when there's CAR

114
00:06:53.756 --> 00:06:57.536
T or TCR T therapy, you see that there's a synergy between

115
00:06:57.856 --> 00:07:01.796
the two. And actually, the mechanism behind it is that there's an

116
00:07:01.876 --> 00:07:05.136
increased presentation of the targeted neoantigen.

117
00:07:05.506 --> 00:07:07.576
And this is true across neoantigens.

118
00:07:07.616 --> 00:07:11.096
We've seen this for numerous ones, and we've seen this to be relevant also for

119
00:07:11.156 --> 00:07:12.916
bispecific antibodies.

120
00:07:13.976 --> 00:07:17.156
Challenge number three, neoantigens are often subclonal,

121
00:07:17.936 --> 00:07:19.676
making them ineffective targets.

122
00:07:20.156 --> 00:07:24.016
So our solution is to reduce intratumor heterogeneity

123
00:07:25.176 --> 00:07:29.116
and applying a selective pressure to enrich the clonal

124
00:07:29.156 --> 00:07:31.916
neoantigens that are derived from drug-resistant

125
00:07:31.976 --> 00:07:35.506
mutations. And so we went about to

126
00:07:35.536 --> 00:07:38.956
derive this SpotNeoMet tool together with Nuria

127
00:07:38.976 --> 00:07:40.416
Lopez-Bigas,

128
00:07:41.456 --> 00:07:45.196
which basically takes data from TCGA for primary tumors,

129
00:07:45.556 --> 00:07:49.076
compares them to the Hartwig data for metastatic tumors,

130
00:07:49.496 --> 00:07:53.416
and we run our pipeline to identify recurrent mutations.

131
00:07:53.476 --> 00:07:57.456
We filter all the variants, predict which ones of them are going to be

132
00:07:57.656 --> 00:08:01.156
drivers, and then predict what peptides may be

133
00:08:01.196 --> 00:08:05.016
presented. And so you get quite a few targets, and

134
00:08:05.156 --> 00:08:09.036
really you can see here the targets that are specific for the

135
00:08:09.076 --> 00:08:12.596
metastatic cases, which are patients who received

136
00:08:12.896 --> 00:08:16.676
these drugs. And so these are the ones that we're actually interested in.

137
00:08:16.716 --> 00:08:20.176
And you can see here in a table format some well-known

138
00:08:21.016 --> 00:08:24.036
genes and mutations that are derived

139
00:08:24.756 --> 00:08:27.716
from drug treatments and lead to resistance.

140
00:08:27.816 --> 00:08:30.116
You can also notice that they're all clonal.

141
00:08:30.676 --> 00:08:34.616
And so we decided to focus on just this, but we're now working on all the others.

142
00:08:34.677 --> 00:08:36.175
But this is the androgen receptor.

143
00:08:36.236 --> 00:08:39.016
We proved it to be indeed presented.

144
00:08:39.536 --> 00:08:43.057
It's immunogenic, and we now have three cognate T cell receptors

145
00:08:43.116 --> 00:08:47.096
towards this target. And here

146
00:08:47.176 --> 00:08:50.996
you see an ACT, an adoptive cell therapy treatment with one of

147
00:08:51.036 --> 00:08:54.916
these TCRs effectively rejecting a

148
00:08:54.996 --> 00:08:57.416
tumor that's presenting this neoantigen.

149
00:08:58.156 --> 00:09:01.656
And so that is our solution, or at least one of the solutions for sub

150
00:09:01.716 --> 00:09:02.425
clonality.

151
00:09:03.376 --> 00:09:06.716
Challenge number four is the lack of identifying

152
00:09:06.756 --> 00:09:10.296
neoantigens. So again, low TMB. So we need to

153
00:09:10.316 --> 00:09:13.596
expand the pool of targetable neoantigens, and we need to

154
00:09:13.636 --> 00:09:16.616
consider that cancer-specific

155
00:09:16.696 --> 00:09:20.296
processes will derive cancer-specific

156
00:09:20.306 --> 00:09:23.396
neoantigens. This is reflected on the

157
00:09:23.436 --> 00:09:27.316
immunopeptidome. So we can actually take advantage of the hallmarks

158
00:09:27.356 --> 00:09:30.416
of cancer that may lead to the presentation of

159
00:09:30.456 --> 00:09:33.496
cancer-unique repertoires of peptides.

160
00:09:33.536 --> 00:09:37.425
This is beyond the well-known classical somatic mutation-derived

161
00:09:37.476 --> 00:09:41.436
neopeptides. And so we started off by looking at bacterial antigens,

162
00:09:42.396 --> 00:09:45.496
because we know that bacteria populate tumors.

163
00:09:46.136 --> 00:09:49.796
And so with Oved Strassman and Jennifer Wargo, we

164
00:09:50.456 --> 00:09:53.876
sequenced 16S RNA sequencing to

165
00:09:53.956 --> 00:09:57.336
identify the microbiome in numerous metastatic

166
00:09:57.376 --> 00:10:01.356
melanoma samples, and then performed immunopeptidomics

167
00:10:01.576 --> 00:10:05.425
on these samples and basically analyzed the data a bit differently.

168
00:10:05.516 --> 00:10:08.976
We added the protein sequences of the identified

169
00:10:09.056 --> 00:10:11.676
bacteria into the database and

170
00:10:12.496 --> 00:10:16.476
then checked whether any of the masses of the peptides that we identified by

171
00:10:16.485 --> 00:10:19.476
immunopeptidomics aligns to bacterial

172
00:10:19.876 --> 00:10:23.656
sequences. And indeed, to our surprise, quite a few

173
00:10:23.836 --> 00:10:27.746
HLA class I and HLA class II-derived peptides were identified, and

174
00:10:27.836 --> 00:10:30.076
quite a few of them were immunogenic.

175
00:10:30.196 --> 00:10:34.055
So this is one way to enlarge the antigenic space, even though we've still

176
00:10:34.115 --> 00:10:36.496
not proven that these are cancer specific.

177
00:10:37.836 --> 00:10:41.586
Another set of hallmarks is that there's

178
00:10:41.616 --> 00:10:45.536
dysregulation of the translation fidelity components in

179
00:10:45.576 --> 00:10:48.516
cancer. And this is especially true when there's a

180
00:10:49.936 --> 00:10:52.536
stress response within the cells.

181
00:10:52.546 --> 00:10:54.806
And so we decided to look into this,

182
00:10:55.916 --> 00:10:59.756
specifically by looking at high interferon gamma levels

183
00:10:59.856 --> 00:11:03.616
as a stress response. So interferon gamma derived from infiltrating

184
00:11:03.716 --> 00:11:06.376
T cells will activate either one.

185
00:11:07.376 --> 00:11:10.796
Either one will deplete tryptophan forming kynurenine, which will

186
00:11:10.836 --> 00:11:14.676
inhibit T cell function. But the other side of the

187
00:11:14.716 --> 00:11:18.696
coin is that when there's tryptophan being depleted, it will lead to uncharged

188
00:11:18.756 --> 00:11:21.376
tRNAs, which reduces translation.

189
00:11:21.856 --> 00:11:25.756
But the surprising part is that these ribosomes are now

190
00:11:25.816 --> 00:11:29.736
paused on tryptophan residues. And despite the fact that there's

191
00:11:29.796 --> 00:11:33.596
no tryptophan in the cell, these ribosomes will frame shift either

192
00:11:33.656 --> 00:11:37.356
minus one or plus one, leading to aberrant peptide

193
00:11:37.396 --> 00:11:41.016
presentation, quite a few of which are actually immunogenic.

194
00:11:41.656 --> 00:11:45.516
And we did this together with Oved Nirg 化 mi's lab, and this is really a prime

195
00:11:45.576 --> 00:11:49.276
example for non-mutational peptide antigens that

196
00:11:49.416 --> 00:11:51.036
trigger an immune response.

197
00:11:52.516 --> 00:11:56.116
Now, we know that other stresses will probably do the same.

198
00:11:56.216 --> 00:11:59.716
For example, hypoxia, other cytokines, nutrient

199
00:12:00.256 --> 00:12:04.156
deprivation will lead to changes in the tRNA pool and the

200
00:12:04.216 --> 00:12:08.096
whole machinery leading to translation adaptation and again, altered

201
00:12:08.196 --> 00:12:11.686
proteins and aberrant peptide presentation, increased

202
00:12:11.776 --> 00:12:15.236
immunogenicity. But we also need to consider that intrinsic

203
00:12:15.336 --> 00:12:19.196
drivers may do the same. And when I say intrinsic drivers,

204
00:12:19.316 --> 00:12:22.896
these could be alterations in the translation machinery,

205
00:12:23.116 --> 00:12:26.556
even on the genetic basis, again, leading to

206
00:12:26.616 --> 00:12:29.516
translation adaptation and aberrant peptide

207
00:12:29.596 --> 00:12:33.548
presentation.So in fact, compared to

208
00:12:33.557 --> 00:12:37.048
a somatic mutation that will directly lead to a

209
00:12:37.088 --> 00:12:40.728
neopeptide to be presented, in this case, if there's an

210
00:12:40.788 --> 00:12:44.188
alteration in a translation fidelity factor, it will

211
00:12:44.208 --> 00:12:48.028
amplify the number of aberrant proteins that are found and the number

212
00:12:48.128 --> 00:12:51.488
of aberrant peptides that will be presented,

213
00:12:51.948 --> 00:12:54.268
therefore increasing tumor immunogenicity.

214
00:12:54.688 --> 00:12:56.148
This was our hypothesis.

215
00:12:57.128 --> 00:13:00.688
So we decided to exploit the translation infidelity to expand the

216
00:13:00.788 --> 00:13:04.308
targetable antigenic space, and we chose one

217
00:13:04.468 --> 00:13:07.688
factor called TYW2 as a proof of concept.

218
00:13:08.508 --> 00:13:11.778
Now, what TYW2 does, it adds a

219
00:13:11.808 --> 00:13:15.008
Y-butysin moiety onto tRNA

220
00:13:15.028 --> 00:13:19.008
phenylalanine on position 37, which is just next to the

221
00:13:19.088 --> 00:13:22.908
anticodon loop. And when it adds that Y-butysin, it

222
00:13:23.108 --> 00:13:27.088
stabilizes the ribosomes during translation and prevents them from

223
00:13:27.208 --> 00:13:30.868
slipping. And so the idea is that if we knock out

224
00:13:30.988 --> 00:13:32.048
TYW2,

225
00:13:33.028 --> 00:13:36.328
you'll get hypomodified tRNA phenylalanine.

226
00:13:36.367 --> 00:13:39.578
The ribosomes will slip, there will be aberrant protein

227
00:13:39.688 --> 00:13:43.568
synthesis, aberrant peptide presentation, ultimately

228
00:13:43.628 --> 00:13:46.248
leading to enhanced antitumor activity.

229
00:13:46.788 --> 00:13:49.868
So this was our working plan, and we

230
00:13:50.508 --> 00:13:52.168
stepped through all of these

231
00:13:53.488 --> 00:13:55.268
steps, and I'll show you some of the data.

232
00:13:55.928 --> 00:13:59.628
So the first thing we did was to knock out TYW2 from human

233
00:13:59.688 --> 00:14:03.508
melanoma cell lines, and we used this reporter system from

234
00:14:03.528 --> 00:14:07.008
Tachi Pilpel's lab that harbors a slippery sequence

235
00:14:07.028 --> 00:14:10.888
that's derived from HIV gag-pol with two

236
00:14:11.008 --> 00:14:14.828
fluorescent tags. And when we add this reporter system into our

237
00:14:14.868 --> 00:14:18.628
knockout cells, we can clearly see that there's a frame shift right

238
00:14:18.728 --> 00:14:22.408
here. And by producing this particular product, the

239
00:14:22.468 --> 00:14:24.548
larger product, the minus one product.

240
00:14:25.008 --> 00:14:28.848
And this can be rescued if you put back wild type TYW2,

241
00:14:29.268 --> 00:14:32.448
then you get again the shorter product, and this shifts back.

242
00:14:32.868 --> 00:14:35.388
So on the reporter system, it's looking good.

243
00:14:35.888 --> 00:14:38.348
But we wanted to see what happens endogenously.

244
00:14:38.848 --> 00:14:41.658
So for this, we looked for out-of-frame peptides.

245
00:14:41.748 --> 00:14:44.968
So we took our three TYW2 knockout

246
00:14:45.368 --> 00:14:49.128
clones and performed immunopeptidomics on them and compared

247
00:14:49.168 --> 00:14:52.108
the peptide sequences to the wild type.

248
00:14:52.138 --> 00:14:55.988
And you can clearly see a very nice cluster here of

249
00:14:56.068 --> 00:14:59.968
